---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base title="Our Story">
  <h1>Our Story</h1>
  <p class="label">How and why Project Cognify began</p>

  <div class="prose">
    <h2>It Started With a Simple Question</h2>
    <p>
      Imagine it's a Tuesday night at 2am, and both of you want to go to sleep.
      Unfortunately for both of you, a game you have both been following has released a new update.
      It'll be a few hours max after you wake up tomorrow morning before you get spoiled by social media.
      This is the scenario where I came up with the hypothesis:
    </p>
      Why is it so easy to spend hours focused on a game, yet so difficult to
      spend thirty minutes focused on studying or work?
    <p>
      The more I thought about it, the more I realized this wasn't just my
      experience. Most students I know deal with the same thing.
    </p>
    <p>Instead of guessing at the answer, I decided to investigate it.</p>

    <h2>Becoming a Team</h2>
    <p>
      I knew this would go better as a team effort. Since Jeremy and Ryan had worked
      with me during a game jam the year before, the choice was obvious. We approached problems
      differently, but we worked well together. Nobody was afraid to
      challenge each other.
    </p>
    <p>
      When I shared what I was thinking, neither of them asked what app we were
      going to build. They asked what we actually knew.
    </p>
    <p>The honest answer was "not much."</p>
    <p>That was the moment Project Cognify became a real project.</p>

    <h2>Why We're Doing This</h2>
    <p>
      Like most students, we know how hard it is to stay focused when everything
      is competing for attention. Phones, notifications, social media,
      games. All of it is designed to keep us engaged, and it works.
    </p>
    <p>
      Most solutions focus on removing distractions. We wanted to explore a
      different question:
    </p>
      What if the same psychology that keeps us engaged in games could help us
      stay focused on things that matter?
    <p>
      We don't know if that's possible yet. That's exactly what we're trying to
      find out.
    </p>

    <h2>How We're Approaching It</h2>
    <p>Instead of starting with a solution, we're starting with questions.</p>
    <p>
      We're reviewing academic research, surveying students, and conducting
      interviews, and letting what we learn shape what we build. If the evidence
      supports our original idea, we'll keep going. If it points somewhere else,
      we'll change course.
    </p>
    <p>
      That's already happened once. Our hypothesis changed after our first
      survey. You can read about it in the <a href="/devlog">devlog</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Why We're Sharing Everything</h2>
    <p>
      Most projects only show the finished product, but we wanted to do something
      different.
    </p>
    <p>
      This website documents everything along the way, including our research,
      ideas, prototypes, mistakes, and what we learn from them.
    </p>
    <p>
      If this project helps even a few students understand their own focus
      better, we'll consider that a success.
    </p>

    <h2>A Note From the Team</h2>
    <p>
      We're three high school students who became curious about a problem we
      experience daily.
    </p>
    <p>
      While we aren't experts in everything we do, we promise to always try our best to provide
      our best possible effort to others.
    </p>
    <p>Thank you for following our journey.</p>
  </div>
</Base>

